SIMPLE: antipathy
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Antipathy
<hw>An*tip"a*thy</hw> <pr>(⟦acr⟧n*t⟦icr⟧p"⟦adot⟧*th⟦ycr⟧)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Antipathies</plw>
<pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>antipathia</ets>, Gr.
<grk>'antipa`qeia</grk>; <grk>'anti`</grk> against + <grk>paqei^n</grk>
to suffer. Cf. F. <ets>antipathie</ets>. See <er>Pathos</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Contrariety or opposition in feeling; settled aversion
or dislike; repugnance; distaste.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Inveterate <qex>antipathies</qex> against particular nations, and
passionate attachments to others, are to be avoided.</q>
<rj><qau>Washington.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Natural contrariety; incompatibility; repugnancy of
qualities; <as>as, oil and water have <ex>antipathy</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A habit is generated of thinking that a natural
<qex>antipathy</qex> exists between hope and reason.</q> <rj><qau>I.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Antipathy</xex> is opposed to <ant>sympathy</ant>.
It is followed by <xex>to</xex>, <xex>against</xex>, or
<xex>between</xex>; also sometimes by <xex>for</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Hatred; aversion; dislike; disgust; distaste;
enmity; ill will; repugnance; contrariety; opposition. See
<er>Dislike</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Antipeptone</ent>⟦br⟧
